  "prompt": "Can a private company take loan from another private company as per provision of Companies Act 2013?",
  "response": "Yes, under the Companies Act, 2013, a private company can take loans from another private company. However, there are certain provisions and compliance requirements that need to be adhered to. Here are some key aspects:\n\n1. **Board Approval**: The borrowing company needs to obtain approval from its Board of Directors through a resolution.\n\n2. **Provisions Under Section 179**: According to Section 179 of the Companies Act, 2013, the borrowing company must pass a resolution at a meeting of its Board of Directors to approve the borrowing.\n\n3. **Interest Provisions**: The terms, conditions, and interest rates applicable to the loan should be transparent and comply with the provisions of the Act.\n\n4. **Related Party Transactions**: If the loan arrangement falls under related party transactions as defined under Section 188 of the Companies Act, 2013, additional compliance may be required, including Board and potentially shareholder approval.\n\n5. **Disclosure Requirements**: Necessary disclosures about the loan should be made in the financial statements as per the accounting standards.\n\n6. **Deposits Rules**: It must be ensured that the loan does not fall under the purview of deposits as defined under the Companies (Acceptance of Deposits) Rules, 2014 unless it specifically qualifies under the exemptions provided.\n\n7. **Borrowing Limits**: Ensure compliance with borrowing limits as specified under Section 180(1)(c) of the Companies Act, which requires shareholder approval if the borrowing exceeds the paid-up capital and free reserves of the company.\n\n8. **Restrictions on Private Companies**: Private companies might have certain restrictions in their Articles of Association regarding borrowing, and compliance with these internal rules is necessary.\n\nIt is advisable for the company to consult a legal or financial professional to ensure full compliance with all relevant provisions and to understand any implications of the loan arrangement.",
